from his mother's family; his name, then, was P. Caecilius Secundus, his older brother bearing the name Cilo after their father.¹

The Caecilii were a plebeian family of great antiquity. This branch of it had been settled at Comum for several generations. Catullus's thirty-fifth poem is an invitation to a poet Caecilius of Comum to visit him at Verona² Pliny repeatedly speaks of Comum as his patrio.8 It was also the home of his mother's family, the Plinii.⁴
